To compare and contrast the storytelling techniques, character development, and thematic elements in horror films from the 1970s and the modern era, we can organize our analysis into several key areas. Below is a detailed analysis in LaTeX format:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\title{Evolution of Horror Films: A Comparative Analysis}
\author{}
\date{}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
The horror genre has evolved significantly from the 1970s to the modern era. This analysis explores the storytelling techniques, character development, and thematic elements in horror films across these periods.

\section{Storytelling Techniques}

\subsection{1970s Horror Films}
In the 1970s, horror films often employed linear storytelling with a focus on suspense and gradual build-up. The narrative structure typically emphasized:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Psychological Horror:} Films like \textit{The Exorcist} and \textit{Rosemary's Baby} focused on psychological tension.
    \item \textbf{Slow Pacing:} The tension was built slowly, creating an atmosphere of dread.
    \item \textbf{Realism and Grit:} A more realistic portrayal of horror, often reflecting societal anxieties.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Modern Horror Films}
Modern horror films often utilize non-linear storytelling and incorporate various sub-genres:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Non-linear Narratives:} Films like \textit{Hereditary} and \textit{Midsommar} explore fragmented timelines.
    \item \textbf{Meta-narratives:} Movies like \textit{Scream} use self-referential techniques.
    \item \textbf{Fast-paced Editing:} Quick cuts and dynamic pacing enhance the intensity.
\end{itemize}

\section{Character Development}

\subsection{1970s Horror Films}
Characters in 1970s horror films often followed traditional roles:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Archetypal Roles:} Protagonists and antagonists often embodied classic archetypes.
    \item \textbf{Limited Backstories:} Characters were often underdeveloped, serving the plot.
    \item \textbf{Survival Focus:} The main goal was survival against an external evil.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Modern Horror Films}
Modern films offer more nuanced character development:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Complex Characters:} Protagonists have detailed backstories and personal struggles.
    \item \textbf{Character-driven Plots:} The narrative often revolves around character development.
    \item \textbf{Moral Ambiguity:} Characters are not purely good or evil, adding depth.
\end{itemize}

\section{Thematic Elements}

\subsection{1970s Horror Films}
The themes often reflected societal fears of the time:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Supernatural and Occult:} Themes of possession and witchcraft were prevalent.
    \item \textbf{Fear of the Unknown:} Emphasis on unexplained phenomena.
    \item \textbf{Social Commentary:} Reflections on societal issues like war and family dynamics.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Modern Horror Films}
Modern horror explores diverse and contemporary themes:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Technology and Isolation:} Fear of technology and its implications.
    \item \textbf{Identity and Mental Health:} Exploration of identity crises and psychological horror.
    \item \textbf{Cultural and Political Issues:} Films like \textit{Get Out} address racial and political themes.
\end{itemize}

\section{Conclusion}
The evolution of horror films from the 1970s to the modern era shows a shift towards more complex storytelling, richer character development, and diverse thematic exploration. These changes reflect broader societal transformations and advancements in filmmaking technology.

\end{document}
```

This LaTeX document provides a structured analysis of the evolution of horror films, focusing on storytelling techniques, character development, and thematic elements. By examining these aspects, we gain a comprehensive understanding of how the horror genre has evolved over time.
